         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">24/10/79 ¶  ¶ I have gone carefully through the literature on  ¶ Leptorrhynchus elongatus ¶ , dear Mr Tepper, ¶  and now find that the name  ¶ L. elongatus ¶  DC is attached to the large species, alth...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="de">79.10.24</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="de">To Otto Tepper</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="de">RB MSS M198, Library, Royal Botanic Gardens Melbourne.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="de">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">MS annotation by Tepper: 'Reply 3.11.79.' Letter not found.</p>
               </note>24/10/79. </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="de">
               <seg style="">
                  <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ich bin durch die Literatur von <name key="Leptorrhynchus%20elongatus">Leptorrhynchus elongatus</name> sorgsam gegangen, lieber Hr. Tepper, u finde nun, dass sich der Name L. elongatus DC für die grosse Art anhalten lässt, obgleich ihn die meisten spätere Autoren auf die kleinere Species mit gelben Blumen u lang geschnäbelten kleinen Frucht angewandt haben. Für letztere ist der älteste Name L. medius, Cunningham u als synonym gehört dazu L. rhytidanthe Bentham.</seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="de">Mit bestem Grusse</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="de">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd. von Mueller.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="de">
               <seg style="">Ist die Wurzel der grössen</seg>
               <seg style="">
                  <note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                     <p rend="Footnote"
                        style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                        xml:lang="en">grössern?</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <seg style=""> Art mehrjährig, u die der kleinen wirklich immer einjährig? Dies können Sie dort am Besten ermitteln, auch die etwaige Beständigkeit der Blumenfarbe</seg>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 10pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">24/10/79</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 10pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I have gone carefully through the literature on <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                  <name key="Leptorrhynchus%20elongatus">Leptorrhynchus elongatus</name>
               </seg>, dear Mr Tepper,<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">See M to O. Tepper, 21 October 1879 (in this edition as 79-10-21a).</p>
               </note> and now find that the name <seg style="font-style: italic; ">L. elongatus</seg> DC is attached to the large species, although most later authors have applied it to the small species with yellow flowers and long-beaked small fruit. For the latter, the oldest name is <seg style="font-style: italic; ">L. medius</seg> Cunningham, and <seg style="font-style: italic; ">L. rhytidanthe</seg> Bentham belongs to it as synonym.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; font-size: 10pt; "
               xml:lang="en">With best greetings</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; font-size: 10pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd. von Mueller.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 10pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Is the root of the larger species perennial and that of the small really always annual? You can best ascertain this there, also the possible constancy of the flower colour.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Leptorrhynchus%20elongatus">Leptorrhynchus elongatus</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Leptorrhynchus%20medius">Leptorrhynchus medius</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Leptorrhynchus%20rhytidanthe">Leptorrhynchus rhytidanthe</name>
            </p>
         </div>
